he spread of railroads, the emergence of rifled small arms and artillery, the introduction of battle tanks, and the nuclear revolution. Lieber incorporates the new historiography of World War I, which draws on archival materials that only recently became available, to challenge many common beliefs about the conflict. The author's central conclusion is that technology is neither a cause of international conflict nor a panacea; instead, power politics remains paramount.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2019) 0aMilitary art and sciencexPolitical aspectsvCase studies. 0aMilitary art and sciencexTechnological innovationsxHistoryy19th centuryvCase studies. 0aMilitary art and sciencexTechnological innovationsxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aMilitary weaponsxHistoryy19th centuryvCase studies. 0aMilitary weaponsxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aSecurity, InternationalxHistoryy19th centuryvCase studies. 0aSecurity, InternationalxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 4aMilitary History. 4aSecurity Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501724466423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501724466.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG